[{"category":"section","location":"phases/#Phase-functions","page":"Phases","text":"Currently, this package supports the automatic evaluation of a number of special phases. \n\nwarning: Warning\nUsage of RationalPhase has not been fully tested and might break if too many poles are given.","title":"Phase functions"},{"category":"type","location":"phases/#NumericalSteepestDescent.PolynomialPhase","page":"Phases","text":"PolynomialPhase(coefs::Vector)  # polynomial coefficients\n\nReturn a PolynomialPhase object representing the phase defined by \n\ng(z) = sum_j=0^J alpha_j z^j\n\nwhere alpha_j are the coefficients in coefs and J is the degree of the polynomial.\n\nIt is assumed that alpha_J neq 0 and J geq 2. For linear phases, use LinearPhase instead.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"NumericalSteepestDescent.PolynomialPhase"},{"category":"type","location":"phases/#NumericalSteepestDescent.LinearPhase","page":"Phases","text":"LinearPhase()\n\nReturn a LinearPhase object representing the phase defined by \n\ng(z) = z\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"NumericalSteepestDescent.LinearPhase"},{"category":"type","location":"phases/#NumericalSteepestDescent.SquareRootPhase","page":"Phases","text":"SquareRootPhase(a, b)\n\nReturn a SquareRootPhase object representing the phase defined by \n\ng(z) = sqrtz^2+a^2 + bz\n\nwhere a0 and b in -11.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"NumericalSteepestDescent.SquareRootPhase"},{"category":"type","location":"phases/#NumericalSteepestDescent.RationalPhase","page":"Phases","text":"RationalPhase(cpoly::Vector, poles::Vector, cs::Vector)\n\nReturn a RationalPhase object representing the phase defined by \n\ng(z) = sum_j=0^J alpha_j z^j + sum_p=1^P sum_k=1^K_p fracalpha_pk(z-z_p)^k\n\nwhere alpha_j are the coefficients in cpoly and J is the degree of the polynomial part, z_p are the poles in poles, alpha_pk are the coefficients in cs[p] and K_p is the order of the pole z_p.\n\nIt is assumed that the singular part is non-zero (i.e. cs is not a vector of zero vectors).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"NumericalSteepestDescent.RationalPhase"},{"category":"section","location":"#NumericalSteepestDescent.jl","page":"Home","text":"NumericalSteepestDescent.jl is a Julia package for the numerical evaluation of highly oscillatory integrals. The aim is to efficiently evaluate integrals of the form\n\nI = int_a^b f(z)exp(mathrmiomega g(z)) mathrmdz\n\nwhere g is phase, f is amplitude, omega0 is a (potentially large) frequency parameter, and the endpoints a and b may be finite or infinite. Further, it is assumed that I is a convergent integral and that both f and g are slowly-varying functions.\n\nThis package is an automatic implementation of a Regularised Numerical Steepest Descent method, but it can be used without a deep understanding of the underlying mathematics. For a full explanation, the interested reader is referred to [1]. \n\nThe simplest use case is integrating with a polynomial phase function. To evaluate the integral\n\nint_-1^1 e^iomega z^2 dz\n\ntry the following:\n\nusing NumericalSteepestDescent\nPhase = PolynomialPhase([0,0,1]) # Define the phase: g(z) = z²\na, b = -1.0, 1.0 # Integration endpoints\nf(z) = 1.0  # # Amplitude function (can be any function)\nω = 1000.0 # Frequency parameter\nnsd([a, b], f, Phase, ω)\n\nFor the case of arbitrary polynomial phase, there is also a MATLAB implementation available [2]. ","title":"NumericalSteepestDescent.jl"},{"category":"section","location":"#References","page":"Home","text":"[1] A. Gibbs, D.P. Hewett, D. Huybrechs, (2024) Numerical evaluation of oscillatory integrals via automated steepest descent contour deformation. Journal of Computational Physics, Volume 501, 112787, https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jcp.2024.112787.\n\n[2] Gibbs, A., (2025). PathFinder: A Matlab/Octave package for oscillatory integration. Journal of Open Source Software, 10(114), 6902, https://doi.org/10.21105/joss.06902","title":"References"},{"category":"section","location":"use/#Basic-use","page":"Usage","text":"The basic interface is the following\n\nExample: determine the quasi-SD contour deformation for an integral representation of the Airy function [DLMF, eq.(9.5.4)]\n\nPhase = PolynomialPhase(-im*[0,+2,0,1/3]) \na, b = -π/3, π/3 # (∞exp(-im*π/3), ∞exp(im*π/3))\nf(z) = 1.0 \nω = 1.0 # Frequency parameter\nai, fig = nsd([a, b], f, Phase, ω; infcontour = [true, true],\n    plot_sd = true)\ndisplay(fig[1])","title":"Basic use"},{"category":"section","location":"use/#Advanced-use","page":"Usage","text":"There is also a number of adjustable parameters\n\nKeyword Default Meaning\nN 25 Number of quadrature points used on each contour\nCball 2pi Control maximum number of oscillations on non-oscillatory balls (and hence the ball radius)\nNrays 16 Number of rays used when determining the ball radius\nδball 10^-3 Governs when overlapping balls should be amalgamated\nδODE 01 Governs the local step size in the ODE solver for SD path tracing\nδcoarse 001 Tolerance for the increment in corrector step of SD path tracing\nδfine 10^-13 Tolerance of Newton solver for quadrature\nδquad 10^-16 Tolerance for truncation and dropping contours if contribution is too small","title":"Advanced use"},{"category":"function","location":"use/#NumericalSteepestDescent.nsd","page":"Usage","text":"nsd(γ0::Vector, f::Function, G::AbstractPhase, ω)\n\nCompute the oscillatory integral with\n\n    int_gamma_0 f(z)e^iomega g(z) dz\n\nInfinite endpoints can be specified with infcontour.  Returns a vector of figures if plot_graph or plot_sd are specified as true.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"NumericalSteepestDescent.nsd"}]
